  "text": "we see by (A.7) that the zeroes of H n are cancelled and we do not get any poles from H n . Thus we have proven that we have a meromorphic one-form on the reduced curve, y red , with the right poles and residues and with integral periods. [CITATION_1] That ω fulfills (4.6) follows directly from (A.3) given that P Nc is normalized. Before going to the second part of the proof let us get a little inspiration from this case where we assume that the SW-curve factorizes. In the following if x is a point in the upper sheet then (with obvious abuse of notation)x is the corresponding point on the lower sheet. By (A.1) we then get (since y(x) = −y(x)):",
